WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.071
Okay. So I'd like to welcome all of you, and thank you for coming to the Signaling

2
00:00:04.160 --> 00:00:05.700
Pathways in Cancer

3
00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:13.080
Major Symposium. This symposium is dedicated to

4
00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:16.820
the memory of J. Michael Bishop, or Mike Bishop, who I'll say a bit about in a

5
00:00:16.860 --> 00:00:20.720
second. This is the schedule for today, and we'll try to keep to

6
00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:23.460
it because we want people to have a chance to ask questions.

7
00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:27.440
If you do want to ask any questions, please come to the microphones because this is

8
00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:31.180
live-streamed, and people won't be able to hear the questions if you don't come to

9
00:00:31.220 --> 00:00:32.439
the microphone. Okay.

10
00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:35.280
So I guess I can switch the slide.

11
00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:40.060
So for those of you who don't know Mike Bishop, he was a giant in the field of

12
00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:41.260
molecular oncology.

13
00:00:42.420 --> 00:00:46.380
I started graduate school a year after he

14
00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.120
and Harold Varmus made the seminal discovery

15
00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:51.400
that endogenous

16
00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:55.790
genes were related to retroviral oncogenes, and in

17
00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:59.280
particular, that the viral SRC gene was related to

18
00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:03.040
c-SRC. And it's difficult at this point to overstate

19
00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:06.320
the excitement that was engendered by that discovery,

20
00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:11.340
and I think that that discovery began what I called in a recent

21
00:01:11.420 --> 00:01:15.240
student lecture, the grand convergence that unified viral

22
00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:19.300
oncology, cancer genetics, chemical carcinogenesis, and chromosome

23
00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:21.540
biology related to cancer.

24
00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:23.000
So

25
00:01:24.140 --> 00:01:24.720
Mike was

26
00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:29.820
a very wide-ranging individual. He

27
00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:33.760
actually was very polymathic. He was a great

28
00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:34.280
writer.

29
00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:39.050
He didn't just serve as a scientist who won major awards,

30
00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:42.900
including the Nobel Prize for that discovery and the Lasker Award, but also

31
00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:46.600
was the chancellor of UCSF for many years and led the expansion of

32
00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:50.600
UCSF into Mission Bay, where a

33
00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:52.240
lot of its science is located today.

34
00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:54.000
So this has actually been a

35
00:01:55.540 --> 00:01:59.340
bad year for losing giants in our field.

36
00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:03.960
But no one was bigger than Mike, and it's an honor

37
00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:07.760
to chair a symposium that's dedicated to his

38
00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:09.420
memory. And in fact,

39
00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:14.320
the topic of this session is a direct outgrowth of his

40
00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:18.220
original discovery. So this session is going to focus largely

41
00:02:18.340 --> 00:02:22.040
on two signaling pathways that are essential downstream of receptor tyrosine

42
00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:24.260
kinases and also other receptors.

43
00:02:24.730 --> 00:02:28.480
And these pathways are the RAS/ERK/MAPK kinase pathway and the PI3

44
00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:32.320
kinase/AKT/mTOR pathway. And we'll

45
00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:32.640
have

46
00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.900
talks in the meeting from John Blenis

47
00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:41.840
on the mTOR/AKT pathway. I'll be talking about SHP2, which is at

48
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:44.580
the beginning of the RAS/MAPK kinase pathway.

49
00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:48.220
And Debbie Morrison will be speaking about RAF family

50
00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:51.100
kinases, which are also in the RAS/ERK pathway.

51
00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:54.060
And then, of course, these signals are transmitted to the nucleus where they

52
00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:57.160
regulate gene expression. And our

53
00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:01.240
rising star speaker, Ray Pillai, who's from

54
00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:05.600
NYU, also will be telling us about one of the downstream

55
00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:07.880
consequences of signaling through these pathways.

56
00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:11.820
And I've noted on this slide how the components

57
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:15.760
of these pathways are really a robust source of oncogenes

58
00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:19.580
and tumor suppressor genes, the oncogenes being shown in red and the tumor

59
00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:21.950
suppressor genes being shown in green.

60
00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:26.160
So without any further ado, we'll start with my

61
00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:26.600
talk.

62
00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:30.500
Give me a second while it switches.

63
00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:37.620
Okay. So the work that I'm going to talk about today on new

64
00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:41.650
insights into how SHP2 signals to RAS is really the result of

65
00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:42.140
a very

66
00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:47.430
detailed collaboration between my lab, the labs of Wolfgang Petty and

67
00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:51.200
Rebecca Page at UConn, who have contributed all the

68
00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:54.790
structural biology that I'll be talking about at the end of the talk, and

69
00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.740
also some work by Jeroen den Hertog

70
00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:01.880
in the Netherlands at Utrecht on zebrafish SHP2.

71
00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:06.140
And the phosphatase community is a very nice community, and everybody was

72
00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.760
really interested in solving this problem, and we all got together.

73
00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:13.640
It's not solved yet, but I think we've made substantial and shocking progress in

74
00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:15.930
the last couple of years. These are my disclosures.

75
00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:19.469
Everything that's shown in red is peripherally relevant to this talk,

76
00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:22.860
but I won't be talking about any work from any of these companies here.

77
00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:24.810
It's all from the labs that I mentioned.

78
00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:26.960
So this is a cartoon-like structure of SHP2.

79
00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:30.900
It has two N-terminal SH2 domains, a central PTP domain, and a

80
00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:34.700
C-terminus with two tyrosine phosphorylation sites that in response to many

81
00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:38.460
receptors, but not all, can become tyrosine phosphorylated, and they

82
00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.740
constitute binding sites for the adaptor GRAB2.

83
00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.680
And SHP2 is expressed ubiquitously, and it regulates

84
00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:49.120
normal cell survival and proliferation, primarily by the

85
00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:52.900
RAS/ERK pathway, and that's why it's in this part of the

86
00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:56.400
session today. It's required for RTK and PTK

87
00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:59.960
fusion-derived malignancies and also for adaptive resistance to

88
00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:03.960
RAS/ERK/MAP kinase pathway inhibitors.

89
00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:08.460
But in addition, there are somatic mutations in SHP2 that

90
00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:11.940
are associated with several leukemias, most prominently juvenile

91
00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:15.740
myelomonocytic leukemia, which I'll say JMML in the future

92
00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:17.640
because I can't say that fast enough,

93
00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:22.700
and also some solid tumors in humans, especially in response to

94
00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:25.720
other inhibitors. It's been

95
00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:30.490
argued to have a role in checkpoint receptor signaling, particularly PD-1, but

96
00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.520
four labs, including our own, have knocked out SHP2 in T-cells,

97
00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:36.260
and there's no effect on PD-1 action.

98
00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:38.540
In fact, PD-1 action is, if anything, enhanced.

99
00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:40.580
So I think that remains questionable.

100
00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:44.920
And there are multiple allosteric inhibitors that have been in clinical trials.

101
00:05:44.950 --> 00:05:48.180
There's only a few that are still in inhibitors in clinical trials.

102
00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:49.760
And as I'll show you on the next slide,

103
00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:54.540
these allosteric inhibitors prevent the opening of SHP2, and

104
00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:58.040
therefore, they shouldn't be viewed as typical kinase

105
00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:02.020
inhibitors or other types of inhibitors as enzymatic inhibitors, but they're

106
00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:05.128
really more like protein nulls.So,

107
00:06:06.168 --> 00:06:10.108
there are two potential models for how SHP2 regulates

108
00:06:11.588 --> 00:06:13.708
RAS ERK activation downstream of

109
00:06:14.548 --> 00:06:18.428
receptor tyrosine kinases. And it's been known now for at least

110
00:06:18.568 --> 00:06:22.448
20 years that SHP2 lies upstream of the RAS exchange factor SOS.

111
00:06:23.308 --> 00:06:26.888
But even earlier than that, two groups, our group and Josi Schlesinger's group in

112
00:06:26.928 --> 00:06:30.478
1994, when many of you in the audience were probably not born,

113
00:06:31.368 --> 00:06:34.728
suggested that an adapter model where recruitment of

114
00:06:34.748 --> 00:06:38.568
GRAB2 to those tyrosine phosphorylation sites in the C-terminus brought

115
00:06:38.588 --> 00:06:41.048
SOS to the membrane and activated RAS.

116
00:06:41.508 --> 00:06:45.488
And subsequently, our group and also Xin Jiang's group have shown that

117
00:06:46.648 --> 00:06:48.748
that is not true for all receptors.

118
00:06:48.828 --> 00:06:52.048
So in particular, in work that we have in-- That we

119
00:06:52.128 --> 00:06:56.028
re-investigated this using mouse models, we've shown that it's required

120
00:06:56.088 --> 00:06:59.788
for PDGF signaling and it's partially required for

121
00:06:59.888 --> 00:07:03.068
FGF signaling, but it's completely dispensable for EGF signaling.

122
00:07:03.388 --> 00:07:06.668
And that confirms work that we published in early 2000.

123
00:07:08.008 --> 00:07:11.548
The other major model for signaling is what I would call the substrate model, in

124
00:07:11.588 --> 00:07:15.227
which case SHP2 acts as an enzyme to

125
00:07:15.288 --> 00:07:18.648
dephosphorylate one or more, as yet unidentified or

126
00:07:18.688 --> 00:07:21.948
controversial substrates. And I can say

127
00:07:21.988 --> 00:07:24.848
conservatively, including by people in this room,

128
00:07:25.428 --> 00:07:29.408
that thousands of postdoc and graduate student hours have been devoted to try

129
00:07:29.448 --> 00:07:30.858
to identify that substrate.

130
00:07:31.788 --> 00:07:35.738
And I'll give you a spoiler alert. I'm not going to tell you what the substrate is

131
00:07:35.748 --> 00:07:37.928
today, and that's because there isn't one.

132
00:07:40.208 --> 00:07:42.978
Okay. So the way we came about this was,

133
00:07:44.048 --> 00:07:48.008
we took advantage of those allosteric inhibitors that I told you about,

134
00:07:48.368 --> 00:07:51.908
and we know that there are mutations that you can make in SHP2 that don't affect

135
00:07:51.948 --> 00:07:55.688
SHP2 function, but that block its ability to bind the allosteric

136
00:07:55.748 --> 00:07:59.328
inhibitors. And the primary one that we use in this, and that I'll be using in the

137
00:07:59.368 --> 00:08:03.008
talk, is TMQL mutant. So what we do is we express,

138
00:08:03.828 --> 00:08:07.308
sometimes inducibly, but sometimes constitutively, at levels similar

139
00:08:07.748 --> 00:08:10.228
to the endogenous level, the TMQL mutant.

140
00:08:10.608 --> 00:08:13.868
And then when we want to expose the-- And then we make second site

141
00:08:13.908 --> 00:08:17.857
mutations in the TMQL SHP2, and

142
00:08:17.868 --> 00:08:21.288
then we add the drug, and that inhibits the endogenous SHP2 and

143
00:08:21.328 --> 00:08:25.088
exposes the effect of the mutant and allows us to determine the

144
00:08:25.098 --> 00:08:28.778
effect of second site mutations. And that's how we found some of

145
00:08:28.828 --> 00:08:32.639
that work I told you on the tyrosine phosphorylation site mutants that I don't have

146
00:08:32.668 --> 00:08:36.448
time to show you today. So the first big surprise is shown on this

147
00:08:36.509 --> 00:08:39.228
slide. So what you can see is that if you stimulate

148
00:08:40.028 --> 00:08:43.668
RAS 3T3 cells with EGF and measure RAS

149
00:08:43.708 --> 00:08:47.528
activation by a GLISA assay or by a direct pull-down

150
00:08:47.608 --> 00:08:51.297
assay, you can see that a potent SHP2 inhibitor such as

151
00:08:51.388 --> 00:08:55.288
RMZ-4550 completely blocks the activation of RAS by

152
00:08:55.308 --> 00:08:58.648
SHP2 at two minutes of stimulation.

153
00:08:58.668 --> 00:09:02.428
And if you re-express the TMQL mutant in the same cells

154
00:09:03.108 --> 00:09:06.708
that's wild type, you can see that you completely restore RAS activation.

155
00:09:07.308 --> 00:09:11.008
Now, we found that two different mutants, the CE mutant, so cysteine

156
00:09:11.068 --> 00:09:14.968
to the essential catalytic cysteine to glutamate mutation,

157
00:09:15.048 --> 00:09:18.588
or the cysteine to threonine mutation, only restored about

158
00:09:18.748 --> 00:09:22.688
50% of activity. So right away, that was problematic because that should

159
00:09:22.728 --> 00:09:26.148
be phosphatase dead, and it's only required for half the signal

160
00:09:26.488 --> 00:09:29.368
that's being blocked by a full SHP2 inhibition.

161
00:09:30.068 --> 00:09:33.728
But the real surprise came when we exchanged data with Matt Sells and Frank

162
00:09:33.768 --> 00:09:35.848
McCormick, who were working on similar problems.

163
00:09:36.248 --> 00:09:40.088
And they hadn't made all these mutants, and neither had we, but they had made one

164
00:09:40.128 --> 00:09:43.478
mutant that we hadn't. And that was they had made the C to S mutant.

165
00:09:43.878 --> 00:09:47.328
The C to S mutant is a mutant that a phosphatase lab would never make because it's

166
00:09:47.348 --> 00:09:50.968
known to have trapping activity and therefore could give you a gain of

167
00:09:51.008 --> 00:09:53.938
function. But in this case, the C to S mutant was completely dead.

168
00:09:54.398 --> 00:09:58.378
And then we decided to make every mutant, well, not every mutant, but a lot of

169
00:09:58.408 --> 00:10:01.898
mutants to that cysteine. And the really big surprise was

170
00:10:01.948 --> 00:10:05.868
that this C to D mutation was not only wild type, but as you'll

171
00:10:05.908 --> 00:10:08.068
see in the next slide, slightly hypermorphic.

172
00:10:08.448 --> 00:10:12.038
So a mutation of the catalytic cysteine to-- First of all, different

173
00:10:12.068 --> 00:10:15.548
mutations of the catalytic cysteine have different effects.

174
00:10:15.577 --> 00:10:19.228
And second of all, mutation of the catalytic cysteine to

175
00:10:19.248 --> 00:10:22.788
aspartate is actually normal for signaling, at least at two minutes.

176
00:10:23.207 --> 00:10:26.968
This is not just true for EGF. It's true for FGF,

177
00:10:27.108 --> 00:10:29.688
as shown on this slide, and also for PDGF.

178
00:10:30.068 --> 00:10:33.998
So at least for three major growth factors, there's no requirement that

179
00:10:34.268 --> 00:10:38.008
the C to D mutant is fully capable of activating signaling.

180
00:10:38.488 --> 00:10:40.408
It's not just true in fibroblasts.

181
00:10:40.488 --> 00:10:41.508
If you reconstitute

182
00:10:42.968 --> 00:10:46.628
SHP2 knockout HEK cells, you again can restore normal

183
00:10:46.728 --> 00:10:48.368
activation with the C to S mutant.

184
00:10:49.208 --> 00:10:51.548
Sorry, with the C to D mutant and with wild type.

185
00:10:52.488 --> 00:10:53.118
And if you look at

186
00:10:54.988 --> 00:10:56.268
longer times downstream

187
00:10:57.308 --> 00:11:01.008
of RAS activation, you can see that the C to D mutant actually sustains

188
00:11:01.128 --> 00:11:04.828
activation. So at two minutes, it's the same as wild type, but it actually sustains

189
00:11:04.888 --> 00:11:08.768
activation distally to that. And if you look at downstream signaling, you

190
00:11:08.788 --> 00:11:12.618
can see that ERK activation is also sustained, and AKT activation is sustained.

191
00:11:13.288 --> 00:11:16.568
So these data suggest that as you might have expected back in

192
00:11:16.608 --> 00:11:20.168
1992 when we first cloned this molecule, that the

193
00:11:20.188 --> 00:11:24.008
phosphatase activity is a negative regulator and turns off RAS ERK signaling.

194
00:11:24.048 --> 00:11:27.708
But the phosphatase domain has positive signaling activity.

195
00:11:28.328 --> 00:11:32.208
Okay, well, it's one thing to work in these abnormal cells like

196
00:11:32.368 --> 00:11:36.068
3T3 cells and HEK cells.

197
00:11:36.328 --> 00:11:40.068
What about mice? So I can tell you that the same thing is true in

198
00:11:40.088 --> 00:11:43.738
mice. So if you make a C to E mutation and knock it into mice,

199
00:11:44.568 --> 00:11:48.048
what you can see is that this mouse is embryonic lethal at day 12 and a half.

200
00:11:48.468 --> 00:11:51.798
We actually did this before any of those other studies, and we were perplexed by

201
00:11:51.828 --> 00:11:55.658
this because the full knockout, which we made in 2006, is

202
00:11:55.708 --> 00:11:58.458
embryonic lethal at peri-implantation. So it was earlier.

203
00:11:58.468 --> 00:12:00.968
So we already knew there was something funny about the C to E mutant.

204
00:12:01.748 --> 00:12:05.308
If you knock in the C to D mutation, not only is it not embryonic

205
00:12:05.368 --> 00:12:08.188
lethal, it's Mendelian, and the mice are fine.

206
00:12:08.228 --> 00:12:09.748
This is the phenotype of the

207
00:12:10.568 --> 00:12:14.488
C to D mutation. And these mice are viable and

208
00:12:14.588 --> 00:12:18.568
healthy, and they have only mild phenotype, which I'm not going to have time

209
00:12:18.608 --> 00:12:22.246
to discuss, and only in females.This is not just

210
00:12:22.276 --> 00:12:25.776
true in mice, it's also true all the way down to zebrafish.

211
00:12:25.816 --> 00:12:29.416
And here we collaborated with Sarun Thanharttakul's lab, and particularly

212
00:12:29.436 --> 00:12:32.076
Daniel Witterson, and more recently Tammy Belsha.

213
00:12:32.586 --> 00:12:36.576
And in zebrafish, if you knock out both alleles of SHIP2,

214
00:12:36.636 --> 00:12:39.836
there's two alleles of SHIP2, PTLN1 A and B, there's no

215
00:12:39.956 --> 00:12:43.196
swim bladder and there's cardiac defect,

216
00:12:43.276 --> 00:12:47.216
cardiac edema. You can rescue that with wild-type zebrafish

217
00:12:47.376 --> 00:12:51.216
SHIP2. The C/D mutant is like the null, and the

218
00:12:51.256 --> 00:12:52.956
C/D/D mutant is perfectly normal.

219
00:12:53.355 --> 00:12:56.996
So again, across all those years of evolution, the C/D mutant is

220
00:12:57.036 --> 00:13:00.316
perfectly capable of signaling. So as I mentioned earlier,

221
00:13:00.756 --> 00:13:04.376
SHIP2 in the context of certain mutations in the SH2

222
00:13:04.416 --> 00:13:08.316
domain, can act as a somatic leukemogenic mutation or

223
00:13:08.376 --> 00:13:10.006
myeloproliferative disease mutation.

224
00:13:10.456 --> 00:13:14.036
And the most strongest of these mutations is the E76K

225
00:13:14.076 --> 00:13:17.976
mutation. And you can assay this in a surrogate assay in human TF-1

226
00:13:18.016 --> 00:13:21.516
cells. So you can see that if you express um wild-type

227
00:13:21.576 --> 00:13:25.456
SHIP2 and then you remove growth factor, GM-CSF, that those

228
00:13:25.496 --> 00:13:28.836
cells don't grow. They don't die in TF-1 cells, but they don't grow.

229
00:13:28.976 --> 00:13:29.176
If you

230
00:13:31.016 --> 00:13:34.916
use wild type E76K SHIP2, now you can

231
00:13:34.976 --> 00:13:36.576
see that you get factor independence.

232
00:13:36.636 --> 00:13:40.056
If you put in the C to S mutation with EK, as we have reported in

233
00:13:40.176 --> 00:13:43.336
2006 in mice, you don't get transformation.

234
00:13:43.396 --> 00:13:46.756
But if you put the C/D mutant in, it's perfectly capable of signaling, and even the

235
00:13:46.796 --> 00:13:50.696
C/D mutant itself can confer factor independence to the TF-1 cells.

236
00:13:51.056 --> 00:13:55.016
So both normal and oncogenic signaling can be conferred by the C to D mutation

237
00:13:55.056 --> 00:13:55.616
of SHIP2.

